#  Wang-Zhang’s induction theorem

Inspired by , Wang and Zhang in developed an induction scheme to study the positivity and continuity of the Lyapunov exponent and Cantor spectrum of quasiperiodic Schrödinger operators with $C^2$ cosine type potentials . We observe that the induction theorem can also be used to construct eigenfunctions, which is one of the corner stones in our proof of the arithmetic version of Anderson localization. Now we briefly introduce their induction theorem. The readers are referred to for details.

For $\theta \in {\mathbb R}/{\mathbb Z},$ let $$R_{\theta}=\begin{pmatrix}
\cos{2\pi\theta}&-\sin{2\pi\theta}\\
\sin{2\pi\theta}&\cos{2\pi\theta}
\end{pmatrix}
\in SO(2,{\mathbb R}).$$ Define $$s:SL(2,{\mathbb R})\rightarrow{\mathbb R}{\mathbb{P}}^1={\mathbb R}/(\pi{\mathbb Z})$$ as the most contraction direction of $A\in SL(2,{\mathbb R}),$ i.e., $\|A\cdot\hat{s}(A)\|=\|A\|^{-1}$ for unit vector $\hat{s}(A)$ in the direction $s(A)$. Abusing the notation a little, define $u(A)=s(A^{-1})$ and $\hat{u}(A)= \hat s(A^{-1})$. Then for $A\in SL(2,{\mathbb R})$, it is clear that $$A=R_u\cdot\begin{pmatrix}
\|A\|&0\\
0&\|A\|^{-1}
\end{pmatrix}
\cdot R_{\frac{\pi}{2}-s},$$ where $s,u\in[0,\pi)$ are angles corresponding to the directions $s(A),u(A)\in {\mathbb R}/(\pi{\mathbb Z}).$

For $\theta \in {\mathbb R}/{\mathbb Z},$ let $$R_{\theta}=\begin{pmatrix}
\cos{2\pi\theta}&-\sin{2\pi\theta}\\
\sin{2\pi\theta}&\cos{2\pi\theta}
\end{pmatrix}
\in SO(2,{\mathbb R}).$$ Define $$s:SL(2,{\mathbb R})\rightarrow{\mathbb R}{\mathbb{P}}^1={\mathbb R}/(\pi{\mathbb Z})$$ as the most contraction direction of $A\in SL(2,{\mathbb R}),$ i.e., $\|A\cdot\hat{s}(A)\|=\|A\|^{-1}$ for unit vector $\hat{s}(A)$ in the direction $s(A)$. Abusing the notation a little, define $u(A)=s(A^{-1})$ and $\hat{u}(A)= \hat s(A^{-1})$. Then for $A\in SL(2,{\mathbb R})$, it is clear that $$A=R_u\cdot\begin{pmatrix}
\|A\|&0\\
0&\|A\|^{-1}
\end{pmatrix}
\cdot R_{\frac{\pi}{2}-s},$$ where $s,u\in[0,\pi)$ are angles corresponding to the directions $s(A),u(A)\in {\mathbb R}/(\pi{\mathbb Z}).$

The main object of the present paper is the following *Schrödinger cocycles* $(\alpha,S_E^{\lambda v})$, where $$S_E^{\lambda v}(x):=
\begin{pmatrix}
E-\lambda v(x) & -1\\
1 & 0
\end{pmatrix},   \quad E\in{\mathbb R}.$$ Let $\lambda\ge \lambda_0=\lambda_0(v)\gg 1$ and $t=\frac{E}{\lambda}\in J=[\inf v-2, \sup v+2]$. In this case, there is $B\in C^2({\mathbb T}\times J,SL(2,{\mathbb R}))$ such that $$\label{schcon}
B^{-1}(x+\alpha,t)\begin{pmatrix}E-\lambda v(x)&-1\\ 1&0
\end{pmatrix}B(x,t)=A(x,t),$$ where $$\begin{aligned}
\nonumber A(x,t)=\begin{pmatrix}
\lambda(x,t)& 0\\
0& \lambda^{-1}(x,t)
\end{pmatrix}\cdot R_{\phi(x,t)},\ \ \cot\phi(x,t)=t-v(x).
\end{aligned}$$ <a href="#schcon" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="schcon">[schcon]</a> in fact gives the polar decomposition of the Schrödinger cocycles.  
From now on, let $A(x,t)$ be as above and $$A_n(x,t):=
\left\{\begin{array}{l l}
A(x+(n-1)\alpha,t) \cdots A(x+\alpha,t) A(x,t),  & n\geq 0\\[1mm]
A^{-1}(x+n\alpha,t) A^{-1}(x+(n+1)\alpha,t) \cdots A^{-1}(x-\alpha,t), & n <0
\end{array}\right.    .$$ Abusing the notation a little bit, for $n\geq 1,$ we define $$s_n(x,t)=s[A_n(x,t)],~u_n(x,t)=s[A_{-n}(x,t)].$$ We call $s_n$ (respectively, $u_n$) the $n$-step stable (respectively, unstable) direction.

Set $I_0={\mathbb R}/{\mathbb Z}$ and $g_1(x,t)=s_1(x,t)-u_1(x,t)=\tan^{-1}[t-v(x)]$ for all $t\in J$. Let $\{\frac{p_n}{q_n}\}_{n\geq1}$ be the continued fraction approximants of $\alpha.$ Fix a large $N=N(v).$ proved the following conclusion by induction. Assume that for $i\geq 1,$ the following objects are well defined:

1.  $i$-th step $critical~points:$ $$C_i(t)=\{c_{i,1}(t),c_{i,2}(t)\}$$ with $c_{i,j}(t)\in I_{i-1,j}(t)$ minimizing $\{|g_i(x,t)|,~x\in I_{i-1,j}(t)\}.$

## The critical points and growth of the transfer matrix

<div class="Theorem">

**Theorem 4**. *Let $\alpha\in DC(\kappa,\tau)$ and $v$ be an even $C^2$ cosine type potential. For any $\varepsilon>0$, there exists $\lambda_0(\varepsilon,\alpha,v)$ such that if $\lambda>\lambda_0$, and $t\in\lambda^{-1}\Sigma_{\lambda v,\alpha}$, then there exists a strictly increasing continuous surjection $$\begin{aligned}
\label{C2}
&\mbox{$c_{\infty}(t):\lambda^{-1}\Sigma_{\lambda v,\alpha}\rightarrow [0,1/2]$},
\end{aligned}$$ and there exist $s_{\infty}(c_{\infty}(t),t), u_{\infty}(c_{\infty}(t),t)\in {\mathbb R}{\mathbb{P}}^1$ if $c_{\infty}(t)\in \Theta_\gamma^\tau$ with $$\begin{aligned}
\label{C1}
s_{\infty}(c_{\infty}(t),t)=u_{\infty}(c_{\infty}(t),t),
\end{aligned}$$ such that $$\begin{aligned}
\label{C3}
\|A_n(c_{\infty}(t),t)\hat{s}_{\infty}(c_{\infty}(t),t)\|\geq c\lambda^{-(1-\varepsilon)|n|}, \ \ \forall n\in{\mathbb Z},
\end{aligned}$$ where $c=c(\kappa,\gamma,\tau,v,
\varepsilon)>0$ and $\hat{s}_{\infty}(c_{\infty}(t),t)$ is the unit vector in the direction $s_{\infty}(c_{\infty}(t),t)$.*

</div>

By <a href="#cwc" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="cwc">[cwc]</a> in Theorem <a href="#theorem12" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="theorem12">3</a> (See also Theorem 3 and Theorem 2 in ), for any $t\in \lambda^{-1}\Sigma_{\lambda v,\alpha}$, for all $j\geq 1$ and $m=1,2$, we have $$\begin{aligned}
\label{C4}
|c_{j+1,m}(t)-c_{j,m}(t)|\leq C\lambda^{-\frac{3}{4}r_{j-1}(t)}\leq C\lambda^{-\frac{1}{10}q_{N+j-2}},
\end{aligned}$$ thus there exists $c_{\infty,m}(t)$ such that $$\begin{aligned}
c_{\infty,m}(t)=\lim\limits_{n\rightarrow\infty} c_{n,m}(t).
\end{aligned}$$

By <a href="#cwc" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="cwc">[cwc]</a> in Theorem <a href="#theorem12" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="theorem12">3</a> (See also Theorem 3 and Theorem 2 in ), for any $t\in \lambda^{-1}\Sigma_{\lambda v,\alpha}$, for all $j\geq 1$ and $m=1,2$, we have $$\begin{aligned}
\label{C4}
|c_{j+1,m}(t)-c_{j,m}(t)|\leq C\lambda^{-\frac{3}{4}r_{j-1}(t)}\leq C\lambda^{-\frac{1}{10}q_{N+j-2}},
\end{aligned}$$ thus there exists $c_{\infty,m}(t)$ such that $$\begin{aligned}
c_{\infty,m}(t)=\lim\limits_{n\rightarrow\infty} c_{n,m}(t).
\end{aligned}$$

We first prove $c_{\infty,1}(t)=-c_{\infty,2}(t)$, this is because of <a href="#mzz" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="mzz">[mzz]</a> in Theorem <a href="#theorem12" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="theorem12">3</a>, we have $$\|A_{\pm r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)\|\geq \lambda^{(1-\varepsilon)r_j(t)},$$ this implies $$\|A_{r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)\cdot s_{r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)\|\leq \lambda^{-(1-\varepsilon)r_j(t)},$$ $$\|A_{-r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)\cdot u_{r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)\|\leq \lambda^{-(1-\varepsilon)r_j(t)}.$$ Since $v$ is even, we have $$\begin{aligned}
&\ \ \ \ \|A_{ r_j(t)}(-c_{j,m}(t),t)\cdot\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-u_{r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)\right)\|\\
&=\|A_{-r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)\cdot u_{r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)\|\leq \lambda^{-(1-\varepsilon)r_j(t)},
\end{aligned}$$ this implies that $$\label{use1}
\left|\frac{\pi}{2}-u_{r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)-s_{r_j(t)}(-c_{j,m}(t),t)\right|\leq \lambda^{-\frac{3}{2}r_j(t)},$$ similarly $$\label{use2}
\left|\frac{\pi}{2}-s_{r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)-u_{r_j(t)}(-c_{j,m}(t),t)\right|\leq \lambda^{-\frac{3}{2}r_j(t)}.$$ <a href="#use1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="use1">[use1]</a> and <a href="#use2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="use2">[use2]</a> imply $$|g_{r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)-g_{r_j(t)}(-c_{j,m}(t),t)|\leq 2\lambda^{-\frac{3}{2}r_j(t)}.$$ By <a href="#new" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="new">[new]</a> in Theorem <a href="#theorem12" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="theorem12">3</a>, $$c|c_{j,m}(t)-(-c_{j,m}(t))|^3\leq |g_{r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)-g_{r_j(t)}(-c_{j,m}(t),t)|.$$ Hence $$\label{use3}
|c_{j,m}(t)-(-c_{j,m}(t))|\leq C\lambda^{-\frac{1}{2}r_j(t)}.$$ By <a href="#C4" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="C4">[C4]</a>, we have $$c_{\infty,1}(t)=-c_{\infty,2}(t).$$ We simply denote $c_\infty(t)=c_{\infty,1}(t)$. By the induction theorem (Theorem <a href="#theorem12" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="theorem12">3</a>) we have $$c_{\infty}(t)=\begin{cases}
0 &\text{$t=\inf {\lambda^{-1}\Sigma_{\lambda v,\alpha}}$},\\
\frac{1}{2} &\text{$t=\sup {\lambda^{-1}\Sigma_{\lambda v,\alpha}}$}.
\end{cases}$$ Note that $c_{\infty}(t)$ is continuous on $\lambda^{-1}\Sigma_{\lambda v,\alpha}$, since $c_{j,1}(t)$ converges uniformly to $c_{\infty}(t)$ on $\lambda^{-1}\Sigma_{\lambda v,\alpha}$ and $c_{j,1}$ is continuous, combine these together, we get that $c_{\infty}(t)$ is a continuous surjection from $\lambda^{-1}\Sigma_{\lambda v,\alpha}$ to $[0,\frac{1}{2}]$.

We first prove $c_{\infty,1}(t)=-c_{\infty,2}(t)$, this is because of <a href="#mzz" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="mzz">[mzz]</a> in Theorem <a href="#theorem12" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="theorem12">3</a>, we have $$\|A_{\pm r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)\|\geq \lambda^{(1-\varepsilon)r_j(t)},$$ this implies $$\|A_{r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)\cdot s_{r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)\|\leq \lambda^{-(1-\varepsilon)r_j(t)},$$ $$\|A_{-r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)\cdot u_{r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)\|\leq \lambda^{-(1-\varepsilon)r_j(t)}.$$ Since $v$ is even, we have $$\begin{aligned}
&\ \ \ \ \|A_{ r_j(t)}(-c_{j,m}(t),t)\cdot\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-u_{r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)\right)\|\\
&=\|A_{-r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)\cdot u_{r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)\|\leq \lambda^{-(1-\varepsilon)r_j(t)},
\end{aligned}$$ this implies that $$\label{use1}
\left|\frac{\pi}{2}-u_{r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)-s_{r_j(t)}(-c_{j,m}(t),t)\right|\leq \lambda^{-\frac{3}{2}r_j(t)},$$ similarly $$\label{use2}
\left|\frac{\pi}{2}-s_{r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)-u_{r_j(t)}(-c_{j,m}(t),t)\right|\leq \lambda^{-\frac{3}{2}r_j(t)}.$$ <a href="#use1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="use1">[use1]</a> and <a href="#use2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="use2">[use2]</a> imply $$|g_{r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)-g_{r_j(t)}(-c_{j,m}(t),t)|\leq 2\lambda^{-\frac{3}{2}r_j(t)}.$$ By <a href="#new" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="new">[new]</a> in Theorem <a href="#theorem12" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="theorem12">3</a>, $$c|c_{j,m}(t)-(-c_{j,m}(t))|^3\leq |g_{r_j(t)}(c_{j,m}(t),t)-g_{r_j(t)}(-c_{j,m}(t),t)|.$$ Hence $$\label{use3}
|c_{j,m}(t)-(-c_{j,m}(t))|\leq C\lambda^{-\frac{1}{2}r_j(t)}.$$ By <a href="#C4" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="C4">[C4]</a>, we have $$c_{\infty,1}(t)=-c_{\infty,2}(t).$$ We simply denote $c_\infty(t)=c_{\infty,1}(t)$. By the induction theorem (Theorem <a href="#theorem12" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="theorem12">3</a>) we have $$c_{\infty}(t)=\begin{cases}
0 &\text{$t=\inf {\lambda^{-1}\Sigma_{\lambda v,\alpha}}$},\\
\frac{1}{2} &\text{$t=\sup {\lambda^{-1}\Sigma_{\lambda v,\alpha}}$}.
\end{cases}$$ Note that $c_{\infty}(t)$ is continuous on $\lambda^{-1}\Sigma_{\lambda v,\alpha}$, since $c_{j,1}(t)$ converges uniformly to $c_{\infty}(t)$ on $\lambda^{-1}\Sigma_{\lambda v,\alpha}$ and $c_{j,1}$ is continuous, combine these together, we get that $c_{\infty}(t)$ is a continuous surjection from $\lambda^{-1}\Sigma_{\lambda v,\alpha}$ to $[0,\frac{1}{2}]$.

Now we prove $c_{\infty}(t)$ is increasing on $\lambda^{-1}\Sigma_{\lambda v,\alpha}$, we need the following result: for $t\in \lambda^{-1}\Sigma_{\lambda v,\alpha}$ with $c_{\infty}(t)\in \Theta_\gamma^\tau$, i.e., $$|2c_{\infty}(t)-k\alpha|\geq \frac{\gamma}{(|k|+1)^{\tau}},\ \  \forall k\in{\mathbb Z},$$ by <a href="#C4" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="C4">[C4]</a>, there exists $j_0(\gamma)$, such that for all $j>j_0$ $$\begin{aligned}
\label{C5}
|c_{j,1}(t)-c_{j,2}(t)-k\alpha|\geq \frac{1}{q^{2\tau}_{N+j-1}}, \ \ |k|\leq q_{N+j-1},
\end{aligned}$$ thus by Corollary 3 in , $$\label{use4}
\frac{d \left(c_{j,1}(t)-c_{j,2}(t)\right)}{dt}\geq c>0, \footnote{In case of \eqref{C5}, $\rho_j(t)=c_{j,1}(t)-c_{j,2}(t)$ in \cite{wz2}.}$$ in a small neighborhood of $t$. In view of <a href="#use3" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="use3">[use3]</a> and <a href="#use4" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="use4">[use4]</a>, for any sequence $t_1>\cdots>t_n>\cdots$ with $t_n\rightarrow t$, we have $c_{\infty}(t_n)> c_{\infty}(t)$ for all $n$ sufficiently large.

We are now ready to prove the monotonicity of $c_{\infty}(t)$. We prove this by contradiction, otherwise, there exists $t_1<t_2$ such that $c_{\infty}(t_1)>c_{\infty}(t_2)$, for $\gamma\ll |c_{\infty}(t_1)- c_{\infty}(t_2)|$, there exists $y\in \Theta_\gamma^\tau\cap (c_{\infty}(t_2),c_{\infty}(t_1))$, let $t'=\sup \{t\in (t_1,t_2): c_{\infty}(t)=y\}$ and for $t\in (t',t_2)$, we have $$c_{\infty}(t)<y.$$ Thus there exists sequence $t_1>\cdots>t_n>\cdots$ with $t_n\rightarrow t'$, such that $c_{\infty}(t_n)< c_{\infty}(t')$ for all $n$ sufficiently large which is a contradiction.

For any fixed $N$ and any $\theta\in\Theta^\tau_\gamma$, we have $$\|\theta+k\alpha+n\alpha\|_{{\mathbb R}/{\mathbb Z}}\geq \frac{\gamma}{(|k+n|+1)^\tau}\geq \frac{\gamma(1+N)^{-\tau}}{(|n|+1)^\tau},\ \  |k|\leq N.$$ Thus $T^k\theta\in \Theta^\tau$ for $|k|\leq N$. By Proposition <a href="#theorem12" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="theorem12">3</a>, we have $$\|v_{E_m(\theta)}\|_{\ell^2}\leq C(\gamma,\tau,v,\alpha).$$ By telescoping and Lemma <a href="#tail" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="tail">2</a>, there exists $\delta(\gamma,\tau,v,\alpha,N,\epsilon)$, such that if $|\theta-\theta'|<\delta$, then $$\begin{aligned}
\label{redest10}
\left|\|v_{E_k(\theta)}\|^2_{\ell^2}-\|v_{E_k(\theta')}\|^2_{\ell^2}\right|\leq  \frac{\epsilon C^{-4}}{500(2N+1)}.
\end{aligned}$$ $$\begin{aligned}
\label{redest11}
\left|v_{E_k(\theta)}(k)-v_{E_k(\theta')}(k)\right|\leq \frac{\epsilon C^{-4}}{500(2N+1)}, \ \ \forall |k|\leq 2N+1.
\end{aligned}$$ <a href="#redest10" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="redest10">[redest10]</a> and <a href="#redest11" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="redest11">[redest11]</a> imply for any $|k|\leq N$, $$\begin{aligned}
|u_{E_k(\theta)}(k)-u_{E_k(\theta')}(k)|&=\left|\frac{v_{E_k(\theta)}(k)}{\|v_{E_k(\theta)}\|_{\ell^2}}-\frac{v_{E_k(\theta')}(k)}{\|v_{E_k(\theta')}\|_{\ell^2}}\right|\\
&=\frac{\left|v_{E_k(\theta)}(k)\|v_{E_k(\theta')}\|_{\ell^2}-v_{E_k(\theta')}(k)\|v_{E_k(\theta)}\|_{\ell^2}\right|}{\|v_{E_k(\theta)}\|_{\ell^2}\|v_{E_k(\theta')}\|_{\ell^2}}\\
&\leq \frac{\epsilon C^{-4}}{500(2N+1)}\frac{\|v_{E_k(\theta)}\|_{\ell^2}+C}{\|v_{E_k(\theta)}\|_{\ell^2}\|v_{E_k(\theta')}\|_{\ell^2}}.
\end{aligned}$$ Thus we have $$\begin{aligned}
|u_{E_k(\theta)}(k)-u_{E_k(\theta')}(k)|\leq \frac{\epsilon}{100(2N+1)}.
\end{aligned}$$ By Definition <a href="#defR" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="defR">3</a> and <a href="#def1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="def1">[def1]</a>, one has $$\begin{aligned}
&\ \ \ \ |\mathcal{T}_N\nu_{\theta}(\mathcal{E}^\tau)-\mathcal{T}_N\nu_{\theta'}(\mathcal{E}^\tau)|\\
&=\left|\sum\limits_{|k|\leq N}|u_{E(T^k\theta)}(k)|^2-\sum\limits_{|k|\leq N}|u_{E(T^k\theta')}(k)|^2\right|\\&
+\left|\sum\limits_{|k|\leq N}|u_{E(T^k\theta)}(k+1)|^2-\sum\limits_{|k|\leq N}|u_{E(T^k\theta')}(k+1)|^2\right|\\
&\leq \frac{\epsilon}{50(2N+1)}(2N+1)\leq \epsilon.
\end{aligned}$$ 0◻

<div id="diophantine" class="Lemma">

**Lemma 4**. *For any $\theta\in \Theta_\gamma^\tau$, we have $\theta$ is $\Theta^{100\tau}_{\gamma/100}$- homogenous, i.e., $|(\theta-\sigma,\theta+\sigma)\cap \Theta^{100\tau}_{\gamma/100}|\geq \sigma$ for any $\sigma>0$.*

</div>

Let $\Theta_k=\{\theta\in[0,1):\|2\theta+k\alpha\|_{{\mathbb R}/{\mathbb Z}}<\frac{\gamma}{100(|k|+1)^{100\tau}}\}$, then $\Theta^{100\tau}_{\gamma/100}=[0,1)\backslash\cup_{k\in{\mathbb Z}}\Theta_k$. Thus for any $\sigma>0$ sufficiently small, we have $$(\theta-\sigma,\theta+\sigma)\cap \Theta^{100\tau}_{\gamma/100}=(\theta-\sigma,\theta+\sigma)\backslash\cup_{k\in{\mathbb Z}}\Theta_k.$$ Notice that if $\Theta_{k}\cap (\theta-\sigma,\theta+\sigma)\neq \emptyset$, then $$\frac{\gamma}{(|k|+1)^\tau}\leq\|k\alpha+2\theta\|_{{\mathbb R}/{\mathbb Z}}\leq 4\sigma.$$ It follows that $|k|\geq (\frac{\gamma}{4\sigma})^{\frac{1}{\tau}}$, thus $|\Theta_k|\leq C(\gamma,\tau)\sigma^{100}$ which implies that $$|(\theta-\sigma,\theta+\sigma)\cap \Theta^{100\tau}_{\gamma/100}|\geq 2\sigma-\sum\limits_{k\geq (\frac{\gamma}{\sigma})^{\frac{1}{\tau}}}\Theta_k\geq \sigma.$$ 0◻

